                  <additions>
                     <list>
                        <item xml:id="a1">
                          <locus target="#iv(erso) #iir(ecto) #iiv(erso) #iiir(ecto) #iiiv(erso) #ivr(ecto) #ivv(erso) #74v #75r #75v #76r" facs="002 003 004 005 079 080"/>
                           <desc type="GuestText"><title type="complete" ref="LIT2915RepCh196"/> Incipit: <foreign xml:lang="gez">ሰላም: ለጽንሰትከ: መሠረተ: ነገር: ወውጣኔ:</foreign></desc>
                        </item>
                        <item xml:id="a2">
                          <locus target="#ir(ecto)" facs="001"/>
                           <desc type="GuestText">Attempt of an untrained scribe: excerpt from <title type="incomplete" ref="LIT3108RepCh388"/>, written in a crude hand in pencil</desc>
                        </item>
                        <item xml:id="a3">
                          <locus target="#31v" facs="036"> f. 31v and passim</locus>
                           <desc type="OwnershipNote">mentions the owner, Wäläta Maryam</desc>
                        </item>
                        <item xml:id="a4">
                          <locus target="#74v" facs="079"/>
                           <desc>mentions the name of the scribe: Habtä Maryam</desc>
                        </item>
                        <item xml:id="e1">
                           <desc>Several features of this codex indicate that it was produced in or around the government scriptorium community: the distinctive harags, the tooled leather (particularly the lines and bird’s eye stamps on the edges of the covers), the cleanly-cut text block, the well-trained hand, etc.</desc>
                        </item>
                        <item xml:id="e2">
                           <desc>The inside front and back covers have three interesting characteristics: 1) the turn ins of the leather cover are finely fitted together and trimmed to form an oval-shaped area in the center, through which; 2) multi-colored paper shows (analogous to the colorful fabric that usually adorns this location in de luxe codices); and 3) the paper has areas torn off in ways that indicate there were possibly once mirrors pasted or glued onto the paper</desc>
                        </item>
                        <item xml:id="e3">
                          <locus target="#76v" facs="081"/>
                           <desc>scrawls in blue ink and in pencil</desc>
                        </item>
                        <item xml:id="e4">
                           <desc>Identified in the insurance hand list as Case B1</desc>
                        </item>
                        <item xml:id="e5">
                           <desc>Numbered quires: quires 3–8, <locus target="#q3 #q4 #q5 #q6"/>
                            </desc>
                        </item>
                        <item xml:id="e6">
                          <locus target="#9r #10v #14v #21v #24v" facs="013 015 019 026 029"/>
                           <desc>etc., words of text are written interlinearly</desc>
                          </item>
                          <item xml:id="e7">
                          <locus target="#72r" facs="076"> f. 72r, line 5</locus>
                          <desc>
                            lines of text are written in the upper margin with a symbol (┴) marking the location where the text is to be inserted
                          </desc>
                          </item>
                          <item xml:id="e8">
                          <locus target="#57v #65 #66r #72r" facs="062 010 070 076"/>
